    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with a clear objective: maximize stolen base opportunities and leverage favorable platoon splits against suboptimal starting pitching. **Corbin Carroll** leads the charge as our strongest play (81.24), benefiting from an aggressive +8% jump due to his elevated position in the batting order, despite facing a high-caliber arm in Max Scherzer. **Tyler Soderstrom** (76.91) and **James Wood** (73.32) provide our most efficient high-floor production; **Soderstrom** capitalizes on a weak matchup against Fedde (5.60 xERA) and an ideal cleanup spot, while **James Wood** leverages a leadoff assignment and a favorable park environment to maximize his run-scoring potential. \n\nThe optimizer\u2019s most difficult exclusion was **Seiya Suzuki** (51.44), who fell just outside the starting threshold. While **Suzuki** benefits from a slight boost due to a slow delivery from Freddy Peralta, his raw projection was hampered by poor BvP history and a lack of elite upside compared to the starters. We are opting for the higher efficiency of **Vinnie Pasquantino** (69.30) and **Jose Caballero** (63.88), both of whom are projected to thrive due to favorable platoon matchups. Risk management remains critical today, as several spots\u2014specifically for **Dalton Rushing**, **Luis Campusano**, **Alex Freeland**, **Brice Turang**, **Corbin Carroll**, and **Mickey Moniak**\u2014rely on pending lineup confirmations. Furthermore, players scheduled to hit at the stadium with \"Wind In\" conditions, notably **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Jose Caballero**, and **Vinnie Pasquantino**, face a tangible power suppression risk that we have accounted for in their final efficiency scores.",
